{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 08:37:41.842636", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nSummary\n- Anomaly detected: Host pc_0_1 is misaddressed and duplicates the IP of pc_0_0 (10.0.0.2). This causes false “OK” results in the automated reachability test and isolates pc_0_1 from its leaf and the rest of the fabric.\n- Control plane (BGP) across the Clos fabric is healthy; all EBGP adjacencies are established and leaf subnets are properly propagated.\n- Data plane between leaves via spines/super-spine is functional (verified by reachability from 10.0.0.0/24 to 10.0.1.1).\n\nFindings and Evidence\n\n1) End-host addressing and reachability\n- pc_0_0:\n  - IP: 10.0.0.2/24, default gw 10.0.0.1 (correct for leaf_router_0_0)\n  - Ping results:\n    - 10.0.0.1 (local leaf): OK\n    - 10.0.1.1 (remote leaf): OK\n    - 10.0.1.2 (expected pc_0_1): 100% loss\n- pc_0_1:\n  - IP: 10.0.0.2/24, default gw 10.0.0.1 (incorrect; should be in 10.0.1.0/24 with gw 10.0.1.1)\n  - Ping results:\n    - 10.0.0.1: 100% loss\n    - 10.0.1.1: 100% loss\n- Automated reachability tool showed both hosts as 10.0.0.2 and reported pc_0_0 → pc_0_1 and pc_0_1 → pc_0_0 as OK with RTT ~0.07–0.08 ms. This is a false positive caused by both endpoints sharing the same IP; each host effectively pinged itself.\n\n2) Leaf and spine router interfaces and routes\n- leaf_router_0_0:\n  - eth2: 10.0.0.1/24 (LAN for pc_0_0)\n  - BGP routes: has 10.0.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.8 (from spine 0_1) — OK\n- leaf_router_0_1:\n  - eth2: 10.0.1.1/24 (LAN for pc_0_1)\n  - BGP routes: has 10.0.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.10 (from spine 0_1) — OK\n- spine_router_0_0 and spine_router_0_1:\n  - Each has EBGP to super-spine and both leaves; both install 10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24 learned from leaves — OK\n- super_spine_router_0:\n  - EBGP to both spines; installs both leaf /24s and advertises them to spines — OK\n\n3) BGP status snapshots (selected)\n- All EBGP sessions are up on all routers.\n- Leaves receive 1 prefix and send 2 (their own plus re-advertised). Spines and super-spine show expected leaf /24s in RIB/FIB.\n- No control-plane instability observed.\n\nAssessment\n\n- Network core health: Normal\n  - EBGP adjacencies are established across leaves, spines, and super-spine.\n  - RIB and FIB entries for both leaf subnets (10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24) are present where expected.\n  - Data plane forwarding between leaf subnets is functional (pc_0_0 can reach 10.0.1.1).\n\n- Abnormal behavior: Host addressing\n  - pc_0_1 is incorrectly configured in the 10.0.0.0/24 network with default gateway 10.0.0.1, while it physically resides on leaf_router_0_1’s LAN (10.0.1.0/24). This misconfiguration:\n    - Prevents pc_0_1 from reaching its local gateway (10.0.1.1) or remote networks.\n    - Creates a duplicate IP condition (pc_0_0 and pc_0_1 both 10.0.0.2). Although on separate L2 segments, this confused the automated reachability test (self-ping success reported as inter-host reachability).\n\nFault Localization\n- Faulty device: pc_0_1 (end host).\n- Network devices (leaves/spines/super-spine) operate correctly and advertise/forward routes as designed. No evidence of routing or interface faults on the routers.\n\nRoot Cause\n- Misconfiguration of pc_0_1’s IP addressing and default gateway:\n  - Assigned IP 10.0.0.2/24 and default gateway 10.0.0.1 instead of an address from 10.0.1.0/24 with default gateway 10.0.1.1.\n  - This resulted in isolation of pc_0_1 and misleading monitoring due to duplicate IP appearing on both hosts.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 13664, "output_tokens": 4787, "total_tokens": 18451, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 13440}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3648}}}
